g.text: Joyce Messier: "Oh, I'm not *frightened*, officer. I'd never..." She leans against the railing, looking up at the grey sky.
Joyce Messier: "I'll just keep the Cor-de-Leite in the channel, if that's okay. It's too shallow near the pier..." She winds the mooring line around a post.
Lilienne, the Net Picker: "Aye, ma'am... And it's a jetty, by the way."
Joyce Messier: "It's good to see you here. I only just arrived myself."
You: "Well, it was good running into you." [Leave.]
Kim Kitsuragi: "Do we?" He glances at his watch. It doesn't look like he does.
Joyce Messier: ...then secures the mooring line. "It's good to see you here, detective. I only just arrived myself."
Joyce Messier: "Hmh... How *do* I like it?" She casts her gaze toward the village -- slush melting on the cinder blocks, construction work left half-finished ten years ago...
Perception (Hearing): Water drips down eaves of eternite. The jetty below her feet creaks to the tune.
Authority: What is this? Destruction of property? Hooliganism? Elder abuse? And who is this *scamp*, anyway?
You: "The place is doomed either way."
Joyce Messier: "It's pornographically poor. The street has no name, all the men are dead or missing... and is that the carcass of a motor carriage over there?" She squints her eyes...
Esprit de Corps: "The children carry them up. Come May, the streets will be flooded..." Outside the wind rattles the loose hatches. "*Flooded* with cheap weapons. In angry hands."
Joyce Messier: "Oh jetty, oh jetty...." she responds mournfully...
Joyce Messier: "Then there's the matter of that little scamp in old-lady clothes. She threatened to paint the Cor-de-Leite red. Like blood, you see. Well, I like it the way it is -- white."
Kim Kitsuragi: "What brings you here, madam?"
Joyce Messier: "Perhaps you shouldn't have. I sort of liked it on her..." She leans against the railing, looking up at the grey sky.
Joyce Messier: The woman is tying a complicated nautical knot around the post.
Joyce Messier: She's tying a complicated nautical knot around the post.
You: "So how do you like it here?" (Look around.)
Joyce Messier: "Remind me to tell you one day." She corrects the scarf around her neck. "For now -- how can I assist you in this new location?"
Esprit de Corps: "They're antiques," says Lieutenant John 'The Archetype' McCoy to his partner. "They're digging them up from the catacombs now, fixing them. Old caches from the Revolution. "
Joyce Messier: "Have I told you how they discovered this place?" The wind picks up, her raincoat flaps in the gust.
Joyce Messier: "Hello, detectives." She fastens the end of the line around the post and straightens her back.
Joyce Messier: "You're not alone. Neither do most of these people -- the literacy rate is around 45% west of the river. Fifty years of occupation have left these people in an *oblivion* of poverty."

"Well, your condition has left you no worse off than most of these people -- the literacy rate is around 45% west of the river. Fifty years of occupation have left these people in an *oblivion* of poverty."
You: "Forty-five percent is around where I operate. Things are getting better though."
Joyce Messier: "Hello, detective." She fastens the end of the line around the post and straightens her back.
Jump to: [You: ""So how do you like it here?" (Look..."]
Joyce Messier: "It's just as well -- Lilienne and I are getting on much better. For one, she appreciates the concept of *rent*."
Joyce Messier: "That they don't..." She leans against the railing, looking up at the grey sky.
Shivers: Above you there forms a quilt of altocumulus clouds, twisting into each other. The wind tugs and stretches them over the bay.
You: "Sounds like Cindy the SKULL alright. Want me to book her?"
"Who is this *scamp*? Want me to look into it?"
Joyce Messier: "No need -- Lilienne and I are getting on much better. For one, she appreciates the concept of *rent*."
Joyce Messier: The woman is tying a complicated nautical knot around the post, while occasionally exchanging a few words with the other woman.
The woman is tying a complicated nautical knot around the post while occasionally exchanging a few words with Lilienne, the Net Picker.
Joyce Messier: "Do you know how they discovered this place?" The wind picks up, her raincoat flaps in the gust.
Joyce Messier: "I hear you have singled out a *suspect* and are in pursuit. This is cause for cautious optimism -- I would not want to delay you..."
Joyce Messier: "She could easily just..." She leans against the railing, looking up at the grey sky.
You: "I need your help with something, right away! No time to talk!"
Kim Kitsuragi: "Thank you, ma'am. Do keep an eye on your boat."
Kim Kitsuragi: "Fortunately for you, madam, the RCM is on the scene."
Joyce Messier: "Of course. Jetty. I prefer a good jetty to a pier any day. Jet-jet-jetty..."

Joyce Messier: "Nothing, really... I've had my eye on this jetty for weeks now. So I decided to investigate it personally. This cluster of buildings isn't on any of the official maps, as far as I can tell."
Joyce Messier: "So am I -- and I *do* know how to use one..." She leans against the railing, looking up at the grey sky.
Joyce Messier: "Of course. I hear you have singled out a *suspect* and are in pursuit -- this is cause for cautious optimism. How can I help you at this juncture?"
You: "You're right to be scared. This is all your fault."
You: "Try not to be scared. This is just how the *real* city looks."

Esprit de Corps: It's early spring and the rains are coming. An officer enters a low hut of stone and wood. Inside, weapons are piled against the walls. Rifles with splintering stocks... and swords. Tens if not hundreds.
Joyce Messier: "'Spying' has such a negative connotation. I did track your progress along the coast, however, and decided I would be better able to assist you from here..."
Shivers: Their cloud shadows slide over the ruins of Revachol West -- wherever they pass, the temperature drops slightly but perceptibly.
Joyce Messier: "Of course -- how fortuitous that I'm so close at hand. What do you need?"
Authority: What is this? Destruction of property? Hooliganism? Elder abuse?
Rhetoric: All right. Politics time. Let's *react*.
Jump to: [Shivers: "Above you there forms a quilt of al..."]
You: "You're in no danger." (Whisper) "The working class have no idea what's happening to them."
Drama: Something about the way she says it makes you want to sing.
Inland Empire: This story she will tell only before she *leaves* Martinaise. At the very end of her stay.
Logic: That -- and she's also keeping an eye on *you*.
You: "Have you been spying on me?"
You: "No, I don't know how they discovered it."
"No, you haven't told me how they found it."
Empathy: You detect a note of longing in her voice.
You: "She's a woman. She doesn't know how to use a sword."
Joyce Messier: "Maybe..." She leans against the railing, looking up at the grey sky.
You: "That's just Cindy being Cindy. You can ignore her."
Joyce Messier: "I'm surprised that woman hasn't put me to the sword yet. Maybe she will? You should ask your questions while you can."
Lilienne, the Net Picker: Dark eyes survey the coast leading up to Martinaise. Dull grey metal rests in her scabbard -- a sword. The wind is too loud for her to hear...
You: "Don't worry. I got her sword." (Show it.)
Joyce Messier: "I'm guessing you *don't* know then..."
Joyce Messier: "It's a pity. Most of these people will never know what this place means -- this island of matter. Or why they were ferried over in the first place..."
Joyce Messier: "No matter -- Lilienne and I are getting on much better. For one, she appreciates the concept of *rent*."
Authority: Real men, real politics, real thoughts in your head!
Joyce Messier: You leave her fastening the mooring line around the post rotting in the water.
Perception (Smell): The smell of salt and dog shit in the background.
Joyce Messier: "...maybe there is something else I can assist you with? While you're *hot* in pursuit?"

Joyce Messier: "I knew you would sympathize." She nods. "Most Revacholians will never know what this place means, our home -- this island of matter. Or why they were ferried over in the first place..."
Joyce Messier: ...then secures the mooring line. "It's good to see you here, detectives. I only just arrived myself."
You: "Tell me now, I have time."
